      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman (column, June 9) says Microsoft should be broken up if for nothing else than it hired ''an army of Washington lobbyists to try to get Congress to cut the budget of the Antitrust Division of the Justice Department while Microsoft had its case before that department.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman (column, June 9) says Microsoft should be broken up if for nothing else than it hired ''an army of Washington lobbyists to try to get Congress to cut the budget of the Antitrust Division of the Justice Department while Microsoft had its case before that department.''</p>
        <p>Imagine that, hiring lobbyists in Washington! Of course this was arrogant, and lobbyists' activity at times is abusive and against the public interest, but Bill Gates did not create the ''army'' of lobbyists. They are a product of our government structure and the manner in which we allow it to operate.</p>
        <p>All people and organizations, even Microsoft, have the right to stand up for what they believe and to use the established government power to achieve their ends. We should all be looking more closely at government  and voting accordingly if we dislike its workings.</p>
        <p>VIRGIL J. AIELLO  Boston, June 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
